'''Calendic acid''' (sometimes '''α-calendic acid''') is an [[Unsaturated fat|unsaturated fatty acid]], named for the [[Calendula officinalis|pot marigold]] (''Calendula officinalis''), from which it is obtained. It is chemically similar to the [[conjugated linoleic acid]]s; laboratory work suggests it may have similar ''[[in vitro]]'' bioactivities.<ref name=Yasui>{{cite journal|vauthors=Yasui Y, Hosokawa M, Kohno H, Tanaka T, Miyashita K|title=Growth inhibition and apoptosis induction by all-trans-conjugated linolenic acids on human colon cancer cells|journal=Anticancer Res|volume=26|issue=3A|pages=1855–60|year=2006|pmid=16827117}}</ref>

==Biosynthesis==
Calendic acid is an [[omega-6 fatty acid]].<ref name=Kinney>{{cite web|author=Kinney, Tony|title=Metabolism in Plants to Produce Healthier Food Oils|url= http://www.metabolicengineering.gov/me2005/Kinney.pdf|accessdate=2007-01-11|format= PDF|deadurl=yes|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20060929134832/http://www.metabolicengineering.gov/me2005/Kinney.pdf|archivedate=2006-09-29}}</ref> though not usually listed with this group.  Calendic acid is synthesised in ''Calendula officinalis'' from [[Linoleic acid|linoleate]] by an unusual Δ12-oleate [[desaturase]] (a FAD 2 variant) that converts the ''cis''-double bond at position 9 to a ''trans'',''trans''-conjugated double bond system.<ref name=lipd_library>{{cite web|publisher=Lipid Library|title=Fatty Acids: Polyunsaturated with other than Methylene-Interrupted Double Bonds|url=http://www.lipidlibrary.co.uk/Lipids/fa_conj+/index.htm|author=Christie, William W|accessdate=2007-01-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070112084411/http://www.lipidlibrary.co.uk/Lipids/fa_conj+/index.htm#|archive-date=2007-01-12|dead-url=yes|df=}}</ref> An ''all-trans'' beta isomer has been described.<ref name=Yasui />
:[[File:Ringelblume Blüte.jpg|left|thumb|200px|Calendic acid comes from the pot marigold]]{{clear-left}}

==Effects==
Calendic acid is the fatty acid responsible for the reduction in feed intake and improved feed utilization in mice when calendula oil is added to the feedstuff, as demonstrated by the comparative experiments in the examples using corn oil.<ref name=patent>{{US patent|20050118208|US Patent 20050118208: Powder formulation comprising conjugated octadecapolyenic acids}}</ref>

