{{Infobox power station | name = Kvænangsbotn Power Station | name_official = ''Kvænangsbotn kraftverk'' | image = | location_map = Troms | location_map_caption = Location in [[Troms]] county | coordinates = {{coord|69|43|15|N|22|03|19|E|type:landmark|display=inline,title}} | location = [[Kvænangen]], [[Troms]] | country = Norway | status = O | construction_began = | commissioned = {{Start date and age|1965}} | decommissioned = | cost = | owner = Kvænangen Kraftverk AS | operator = | psps_upper_res = | psps_upper_res_capacity= | psps_penstocks = | psps_lower_res = | psps_lower_res_capacity= | psps_hydraulic_head = 305&nbsp;m | psps_generators = 1 × 44&nbsp;MW | psps_pumpgenerators = | psps_pumps = | ps_units_operational = | ps_units_manu_model = [[Francis turbine]] | ps_units_uc = | ps_units_planned = | ps_units_cancelled = | ps_units_decommissioned= | ps_electrical_capacity = 44 | ps_electrical_cap_fac = 45.7%<!-- 176,000 MWh/year / ( 44 MW * 365 days/year * 24h/day) = 0.457 --> | ps_annual_generation = 176 | ps_annual_gen_year = | website = | extra = }} The '''Kvænangsbotn Hydroelectric Power Station''' ({{lang-no|Kvænangsbotn kraftverk}}) is a [[hydroelectricity|hydroelectric]] [[power station]] in the municipality of [[Kvænangen]] in [[Troms]] [[Counties of Norway|county]], [[Norway]]. It utilizes a drop of {{convert|305|m|sp=us}} between its intake reservoir at Little Lakes ({{lang-no|Småvatnan}}, {{lang-fkv|Pikkujärvet}}, {{lang-se|Čorrojávrrit}})<ref>[http://www.kvenskestedsnavn.no/stedsnavn/view/5968 Kvensk stedsnavndatabase: Pikkujärvet.]</ref> and South Fjord ({{lang-no|Sørfjorden}}, {{lang-fkv|Sutuvuono}}, {{lang-se|Suvdovuotna}}).<ref>[http://www.kvenskestedsnavn.no/stedsnavn/view/6121 Kvensk stedsnavndatabase: Sutuvuono.]</ref> The reservoir is regulated at a level between {{cvt|315|m}} and {{cvt|305|m}}. The Abo River ({{lang-no|Aboelva}}, {{lang-fkv|Aapujoki}}, {{lang-se|Ábojohka}})<ref>[http://www.kvenskestedsnavn.no/stedsnavn/view/5594 Kvensk stedsnavndatabase: Aapujoki.]</ref> is also utilized by the power plant.<ref>Sørensen, Jan. 2013. ''Vannkraftkonsesjoner som kan revideres innen 2022. Nasjonal gjennomgang og forslag til prioritering'' (= Report no. 29). Oslo: Noregs vassdrags- og energidirektorat, p. 268.</ref> Water is supplied to the reservoir by the [[Småvatna Hydroelectric Power Station|Småvatna]], [[Lassajavre Hydroelectric Power Station|Lassajavre]], and [[Cårrujavrit Hydroelectric Power Station|Cårrujavrit]] Hydroelectric Power Stations. The plant came into operation in 1965.<ref>[http://www.nve.no/no/Kulturminneplaner/Katalog/Kraftledninger/18/ Norges vassdrags- og energidirektorat (NVE): 18 Alta – Kvænangen – Nordreisa.]</ref> In 1999 the company received a license to transfer water from the Brenn River ({{lang-se|Buollánjohka}}), Šleađui River ({{lang-se|Šleađuidjohka}}),<ref>[http://www.kvenskestedsnavn.no/stedsnavn/view/6094 Kvensk stedsnavndatabase: Slerojoki.]</ref> and Olbmá River ({{lang-se|Olbmájohka}}). The plant has a [[Francis turbine]] and operates at an installed capacity of {{nowrap|44 [[Megawatt|MW]]}}, with an average annual production of about 176&nbsp;GWh. The plant is controlled by Kvænangen Kraftverk AS, with a 48.2% share owned by Troms Kraft.<ref>[http://www.tromskraft.no/om/selskap/tkp/kraftverk Troms Kraft: Våre kraftverk.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151119040058/http://www.tromskraft.no/om/selskap/tkp/kraftverk |date=2015-11-19 }}</ref>
