[[File:Lamma Winds visitor kiosk tower base.jpg|thumb|Kiosk at the base of the [[Lamma Winds]] [[Nordex]] N50/800kW wind turbine on Lamma Island with displays showing current power output and cumulative energy produced.]] [[File:Hancock County Wind Energy Center visitor kiosk 3059998289 e60b6b5a09 o.jpg|thumb|The Hancock County wind energy center in [[Iowa]]]]
The great majority of [[wind turbine]]s around the world belong to individuals or corporations who use them to generate electric power or to perform mechanical work. As such, wind turbines are primarily designed to be working devices. However, the large size and height above surroundings of modern industrial wind turbines, combined with their moving rotors, often makes them among the most conspicuous objects in their areas. A few localities have exploited the attention-getting nature of wind turbines by placing them on public display, either with visitor centers on their bases, or with viewing areas farther away.<ref name="wind_farm_tourism">{{cite web |url=http://www.canada.com/edmontonjournal/news/business/story.html?id=63a5438a-ae99-4b76-9629-b7b59d238932 |title=Canada wind farms blow away turbine tourists |publisher=[[Edmonton Journal]] |accessdate=2008-09-06 |last=Young |date=2007-08-03 |first=Kathryn |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090425064111/http://www2.canada.com/edmontonjournal/news/business/story.html?id=63a5438a-ae99-4b76-9629-b7b59d238932 |archivedate=2009-04-25 |df= }}</ref> The wind turbines themselves are generally of conventional horizontal-axis, three-bladed design, and generate power to feed electrical grids, but they also serve the unconventional roles of technology demonstration, public relations, and education.
==Notable wind turbines on public display== * Australia ** [[Blayney Wind Farm, New South Wales]] has a viewing area and interpretive centre ** [[Wattle Point Wind Farm, South Australia]] has an information centre * Canada **[[OPG 7 commemorative turbine]] is a [[Vestas]] V80-1.8MW wind turbine on the site of the [[Pickering Nuclear Generating Station]] ** [[Toronto Hydro]] - [[WindShare]] features a [[Lagerwey Wind]] model LW 52 wind turbine at [[Exhibition Place]] * [[People's Republic of China|China]] ** [[Inner Mongolia]]'s Huitengxile Wind Farm has 14 visitor centers to accommodate wind power tourists to the remote region<ref name="zhou_2007">{{cite web |url=http://www.worldwatch.org/node/5286 |title=Residents of Inner Mongolia Find New Hope in the Desert |publisher=[[Worldwatch Institute]] |first=Renjie |last=Zhou |author2=Yadan Wang |date=2007-08-14 |accessdate=2008-11-04 }}</ref> * [[Hong Kong]] ** [[Lamma Winds]] in Hong Kong has a single [[Nordex]] N50/800&nbsp;kW model with a rotor diameter of 50m and a [[Intermittent power source#Terminology|nameplate capacity]] of 800&nbsp;kW * New Zealand ** [[Brooklyn, Wellington, New Zealand]] has a 230&nbsp;kW wind turbine * United Kingdom ** Green Britain Centre, Swaffham, Norfolk - the only wind turbine in the UK that is open for the public to climb. Also doubles as a visitor's centre, cafe and education provider. ** [[Green Park Business Park]] has an [[Enercon]] E-70 2 MW wind turbine<ref name="greenpark_e70">{{cite news |url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qa5379/is_200511/ai_n21384201 |title=Green energy |date=November 2005 |accessdate=2008-11-12 |publisher=[[BNET]] | first=Terry | last=Bolsher }}</ref> adjacent to the [[M4 motorway]], billed as ''the UK's most visible turbine'' ** [[Renewable Energy Systems]] has a [[Vestas]] V29 225&nbsp;kW wind turbine<ref name="power_from_the_wind">{{Cite web |format=PDF |url=http://www.beaufortcourt.com/pdf/BeaufortCourt/WindPower1.pdf |title=Power from the wind |publisher=[[Renewable Energy Systems]] |accessdate=2008-11-16 }}</ref> visible from the [[M25 motorway]] at its headquarters at Beaufort Court, [[Kings Langley]], [[Hertfordshire]] ** [[Scroby Sands wind farm]] has a visitor center at [[Great Yarmouth]] open during the tourist season (May–October) ** [[Scout Moor Wind Farm]] "has become a real tourist attraction"<ref name="scout_moor">{{Cite web|url=http://www.burytimes.co.uk/news/ramsbottomtottington/3926711.Wind_farm_is_in_the_frame/ |title=Wind farm is in the frame |publisher=Bury Times |accessdate=2008-12-12 |date=2008-11-28 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120215192829/http://www.burytimes.co.uk/news/ramsbottomtottington/3926711.Wind_farm_is_in_the_frame/ |archivedate=February 15, 2012 }}</ref> since its 2008 opening ** [[Whitelee Wind Farm]] near Glasgow has become the first wind energy project in Scotland to join the Association of Scottish Visitor Attractions (ASVA). * United States ** [[Ellensburg, Washington]] Puget Sound Energy's Renewable Energy Center at the Wild Horse Wind and Solar Facility, has a 5,000 sq. ft. visitor center, which features numerous exhibits, a conference room, and guided tours to the base of a wind turbine. The center sits on a ridge at 3,500&nbsp;ft. in the middle of the 149 turbine facility (Vestas V80 turbines). The [[Wild Horse Wind Farm]] is open to visitors from 9:00-5:30 daily, from April through November.<ref>http://www.pse.com/wildhorse</ref> ** [[Dorchester, Massachusetts]] - Local 103 of the [[International Brotherhood of Electrical Workers]] installed the first commercial-scale wind turbine within the City of Boston, a 100&nbsp;kW unit from Fuhrlaender on a 35-meter tower with rotor diameter of 21 meters, visible from the [[John F. Kennedy Library]]<ref name="ibew_fuhrlaender">{{Cite web |url=http://www.renewableenergyworld.com/rea/news/story?id=30153 |title=Boston's First Wind Turbine Serves as Example |date=2005-05-18 |publisher=RenewableEnergyAccess.com |accessdate=2008-11-03 }}</ref> ** The [[Great Lakes Science Center]] in [[Cleveland, Ohio]] has a reconditioned [[Vestas]] V27 wind turbine with a [[Intermittent power source#Terminology|nameplate capacity]] of 225&nbsp;kW<ref name="great_lakes_science_center">{{Cite web |url=http://www.glsc.org/press/press.php?id=34 |title=Wind Turbine Project Q & A |publisher=[[Great Lakes Science Center]] |accessdate=2008-10-28 |date=2006-05-17 }}</ref> ** [[Great River Energy]]'s headquarters in [[Maple Grove, Minnesota]] has a [[NEG Micon]] M700 wind turbine, visible from [[Interstate 94]]<ref name="great_river_energy">{{Cite web |url=http://www.wapa.gov/ES/pubs/esb/2008/jul/jul081.htm |title=Great River's new headquarters 'LEEDs' by example |publisher=Reliable Energy Solutions |accessdate=2008-11-01 }}</ref><ref name="energy_model">{{Cite web |url=http://www.startribune.com/local/west/11922246.html |title=An energy model for all to see |date=2007-11-27 |publisher=[[Star Tribune]] |accessdate=2008-11-02 |first=Paul |last=Levy }}</ref> ** [[Laurel, New York]] has a [[Northern Power Systems]] 100&nbsp;kW turbine at the Half Hollow Nursery and private tours of the operating turbine are provided by [[Eastern Energy Systems Inc.]] of [[Mattituck, New York]]. ** [[Lubbock, Texas]] has a [[Vestas]] V47 at the [[American Wind Power Center]] ** [[McKinney, Texas]] has a [[Wal-Mart]] store with several sustainability features, including two wind turbines manufactured by Bergey Windpower, of 1&nbsp;kW and 50&nbsp;kW [[Intermittent power source#Terminology|nameplate capacity]] respectively<ref name="sustainable_walmart">{{Cite web |url=http://www.renewableenergyworld.com/rea/news/story?id=34647 |title=Wal-Mart Deploys Solar, Wind, Sustainable Design |date=2005-07-22 |first=Jesse |last=Broehl |publisher=Renewable Energy World |accessdate=2008-11-01 }}</ref> ** [[Sweetwater, Texas]] has a 2 [[megawatt|MW]] 60&nbsp;Hz [[DeWind]] D8.2 prototype [[wind turbine]]<ref name="bnet_2007">{{cite news |url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m5CNK/is_2007_Sept_6/ai_n25011477 |title=DeWind Plans Wind Turbine Demo Site in Sweetwater, Texas |date=2007-09-06 |publisher=BNET Business Network |accessdate=2008-11-05 }}</ref> for training students in the [[Texas State Technical College]] wind energy program<ref name="block_2008">{{Cite web |url=http://www.worldchanging.com/archives/008271.html |title=In Windy West Texas, An Economic Boom |first=Ben |last=Block |date=2008-07-24 |accessdate=2008-11-05 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090109061905/http://www.worldchanging.com/archives/008271.html |archivedate=2009-01-09 |df= }}</ref>
